               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-205-person1688">
                  HERBERT 
                  MAYO
               <interp inst="t18300527-205-person1688" type="surname" value="MAYO"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-205-person1688" type="given" value="HERBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-205-person1688" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 28th of April, about two o'clock, I was in <placeName id="t18300527-205-crimeloc1085">Newgate-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-205-crimeloc1085" type="placeName" value="Newgate-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-205-crimeloc1085" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-205-off1083 t18300527-205-crimeloc1085"></join>; I felt my coat-pocket had been picked, and missed my handkerchief - I turned, and saw several persons; the prisoner was within one or two of me - I thought he appeared the likeliest person to have it; I watched him - he crossed the way, and then began to run; I followed, and caused him to be apprehended - I did not lose sight of him; when I came up to him my handkerchief lay at his feet - he had run about one hundred yards; I did not see where the handkerchief came from - he was about fifteen yards before me when the officer stopped him; none of the persons I saw near me had run with him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. LEE. Q. How many persons were within five yards of you? A. Eight or ten; I cannot say - he was the nearest; he began to run alone - I kept my eyes on him; I did not see the handkerchief drop from him - he did not walk some yards before he crossed the road.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-205-person1689">
                  JOSEPH 
                  BATES
               <interp inst="t18300527-205-person1689" type="surname" value="BATES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-205-person1689" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-205-person1689" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I saw the prisoner running, and heard Stop thief! called - I saw him take this handkerchief from his bosom with his left hand, and throw it over his shoulder; I was close to him - no persons were so near as Mr. Mayo and myself.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Are you a regular officer? A. Yes; I belong to Farringdon-ward; the prisoner was ten or fifteen yards before me when I heard the alarm -I was sitting at my dinner at the corner of Warwick-square; he tried to knock one or two young men down; there was not a soul to be seen, but the mob who were following him - I took him in Warwick-lane, near Amencorner.</p>

               <p>MR. MAYO. I believe this to be my handkerchief - it is the same pattern.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Is it not a common pattern? A. Yes; but I believe it to be mine; there is no difference between this and the one I lost.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 16.</p>
